<subSubSection id="79E313B9B828B80928283130215FF71C" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" type="description">
<paragraph id="43D66BDEDFDC02AD19396FC82B572A4E" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E7C09B592460A97ED22054366211F822" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">
Usually erect but occasionally decumbent to ascending cerrado perennial with woody xylopodium, vegetative parts villous with long spreading cobwebby hairs; stems several, erect, herbaceous, 20-30(-50) cm high. Leaves sessile or very shortly petiolate, 1.5-4.5 
<normalizedToken id="B5D88E4C4A85495FBA6EE4C245CEB0BD" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.8-1.5 cm, ovate to oblong-ovate; base rounded, truncate to subcordate or sagittate; apex acute or (above) apiculate; margin entire; petiole 0(-2) mm. Flowers solitary (rarely paired); peduncles 20-50 mm; bracteoles 3-5 
<normalizedToken id="E4099E1BBE959ACC1C41A2E5BA0AD13A" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.5-1 mm, linear-lanceolate, finely acuminate; pedicels 5-10 mm; outer sepals 10-15 
<normalizedToken id="17F6FBB061518ECC3482DDF7E1067671" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5-7 mm, ovate, acuminate; corolla 3.2-4 cm long, white, unlobed, midpetaline bands pink, long-pilose, terminating in a mucro; ovary glabrous; style glabrous, divided 8-12 mm above base, persistent in fruit; stigmas 3 mm. Capsule glabrous, unusually large, c. 1 cm diameter; seeds smooth. [
<bibRefCitation id="44BBA77857EB18D83925F61A9DD79D86" author="O'Donell, CA" journalOrPublisher="Lilloa" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="421 - 455" refId="B245" refString="O'Donell, CA, 1950. Convolvulaceas americanas nuevas o criticas I. Lilloa 23: 421 - 455" title="Convolvulaceas americanas nuevas o criticas I." volume="23" year="1950">
<normalizedToken id="030AEFC1E8C97CA1EF37866C60F6F281" originalValue="O’Donell">O'Donell</normalizedToken>
1950
</bibRefCitation>
: 430-431, f. 3]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4674957BE10DFF3A407458925099D582" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D7F4871C01AA4413D48330EC00C540DF" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F87852E963DCDA87CAEF6543B06B73AA" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">
Paraguay (
<emphasis id="853C9572A6099D3F61EAC6B6FC084D4A" italics="true" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Krapovickas et al</emphasis>
. 45901, 
<emphasis id="F77A0F99C5AD29A010809617069B5D21" italics="true" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Hassler</emphasis>
9123, 
<emphasis id="4A01A599F69762046050954E9AE89AF2" italics="true" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Balansa</emphasis>
1056); Brazil: Parana (
<emphasis id="761E7974AA99D7CD4985C2C7440EA787" italics="true" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Hatschbach</emphasis>
3675, 20011, 30722), Rio Grande do Sul (
<emphasis id="7BC86AF04BF9DF71121E5FA281CD1F59" italics="true" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Gaudichaud</emphasis>
659). 0-800 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B541BE56731579CF01DF8C8CA719461D" pageId="94" pageNumber="95" type="notes">
<paragraph id="4A97CA892E068F7754799C6663F07792" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F5C6563E474433A7B3BC3729757956E6" pageId="94" pageNumber="95">Unique species because of its adaptation to the cerrado biome. The erect habit, xylopodium, woolly, often cobwebby indumentum, subsessile leaves and large corolla all render it distinct from other American species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
